    <h1 class=3D"post-title p-name" itemprop=3D"name headline">Investigatin=
g realtime detections on iOS using Unified Logging</h1>
    <p class=3D"post-meta">
      <time class=3D"dt-published" datetime=3D"2024-10-24T12:00:00+00:00" i=
temprop=3D"datePublished">Oct 24, 2024
      </time></p>
  </header>

  <div class=3D"post-content e-content" itemprop=3D"articleBody">
    <p><em>In an attempt to get back into blogging, I=E2=80=99m publishing =
some notes on a current research project I=E2=80=99m working on, rather tha=
n waiting until I have fully chased down every research lead like the other=
 projects I=E2=80=99ve been working on-and-off for over the years.</em></p>

<p>While looking for a new research project, I recently watched an excellen=
t talk by <a href=3D"https://x.com/Helthydriver">Matthias Frielingsdorf</a>=
 on the <a href=3D"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3D3gnGPfKu7FE">Current S=
tate Of IOS Malware Detection</a>. While my career thus far has focussed on=
 desktop and server security, I had heard from friends who work in the mobi=
le antimalware space that iOS presents a unique challenge to defenders.</p>

<p>To summarise my friends=E2=80=99 opinions, Apple=E2=80=99s strong focus =
on security and privacy has created devices that are difficult to exploit (=
especially with advanced features such as <a href=3D"https://support.apple.=
com/en-au/105120">Lockdown Mode</a>), but that once an attacker has comprom=
ised a device it was difficult for the user or external security team to de=
tect an attack, due to the difficulties in getting actionable =E2=80=98live=
=E2=80=99 data from the device at runtime. Matthias=E2=80=99 talk convinced=
 me to learn about iOS security, and how I could apply my expertise in prot=
ecting other Operating Systems to this problem.</p>

