<h1 id=3D"current-detection-efforts">Current Detection Efforts</h1>
<p>The most common technique defenders have in uncovering intrusions on iOS=
 devices is to create a forensic snapshot of the device using the <a href=
=3D"https://it-training.apple.com/tutorials/support/sup075/">Sysdiagnose</a=
> feature. This has been used by <a href=3D"https://www.amnesty.org/en/late=
st/research/2021/07/forensic-methodology-report-how-to-catch-nso-groups-peg=
asus/">Amnesty</a> <a href=3D"https://github.com/mvt-project/mvt/tree/main"=
>International</a>, <a href=3D"https://citizenlab.ca/2021/09/forcedentry-ns=
o-group-imessage-zero-click-exploit-captured-in-the-wild/">The Citizen Lab<=
/a>, and others to great success in the past. But they suffer from two majo=
r flaws:</p>
<h3 id=3D"1-snapshots-give-time-for-attackers-to-hide">1. Snapshots give ti=
me for attackers to hide</h3>
<p>As snapshots have to be manually triggered, can take up to 30 minutes to=
 collect, and only offer a view into the device at that specific point in t=
ime, they give the attacker time to =E2=80=98clean up=E2=80=99 their footpr=
int on the device, removing forensic artefacts their initial exploitation a=
nd execution may have created.</p>
<h3 id=3D"2--you-need-to-know-when-to-make-a-snapshot">2.  You need to know=
 when to make a snapshot</h3>
<p>It is unlikely a user will know exactly when they are compromised. So un=
less the user employs a routine of proactively and constantly taking snapsh=
ots, they might never know the =E2=80=98right=E2=80=99 time to take one.</p=
>

<p>In Kaspersky=E2=80=99s reporting on the <a href=3D"https://securelist.co=
m/operation-triangulation-catching-wild-triangle/110916/">TriangleDB Malwar=
e</a>, they discussed initially being tipped off to the infection via netwo=
rk monitoring. But network monitoring is far from a reliable detection mech=
anism, especially in the age of Global <a href=3D"https://www.cloudflare.co=
m/application-services/products/cdn/">Content Delivery Networks</a>, TLS en=
cryption, and the increasing use of encrypted DNS via <a href=3D"https://ww=
w.cloudflare.com/en-gb/learning/dns/dns-over-tls/">DNS-Over-TLS</a>.</p>

<p>I wanted to investigate if there was a way to get realtime information f=
rom an iOS device, that would either reveal an attack, or at least let a us=
er know that something suspicious has occurred, and that they should consid=
er making a forensic snapshot to investigate.</p>

<h1 id=3D"enter-lockdown">Enter Lockdown</h1>
<p>Remote machines can communicate to a special daemon running on iOS devic=
es called <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">lockdownd</c=
ode>. This communication requires that the remote machine is first trusted =
by a human physically agreeing to =E2=80=98pair=E2=80=99 the iOS and remote=
 machine together, as well as the devices being able to communicate over ei=
ther physical USB, or local WiFi. For WiFi to work, the devices must be on =
the same subnet (more on that later).</p>

<p>To explain both how the pairing and communication works, here is 2 excel=
lent writeups that will explain it far better than I can:</p>
<ul>
  <li><a href=3D"https://jon-gabilondo-angulo-7635.medium.com/understanding=
-usbmux-and-the-ios-lockdown-service-7f2a1dfd07ae">Understanding usbmux and=
 the iOS lockdown service</a> - Jon Gabilondo</li>
  <li><a href=3D"https://github.com/doronz88/pymobiledevice3/blob/master/mi=
sc/understanding_idevice_protocol_layers.md">Understanding iDevice protocol=
 layers</a> - PyMobileDevice3 dev team</li>
</ul>

<p>Once the remote machine is paired with the iOS device, a surprising amou=
nt of both snapshot and realtime data becomes available to query via the cr=
eation one of a number of =E2=80=98Lockdown Services=E2=80=99. These servic=
es became the focus of my research.</p>

<p><img src=3D"https://blog.tofile.dev/assets/ios_trust_computer.jpg" alt=
=3D"Screenshot of an iOS device, with a prompt asking if the human trusts t=
he connected device" style=3D"display:block; margin-left:auto; margin-right=
:auto"></p>

<p><em>Screenshot of an iOS device, with a prompt asking if the human trust=
s the connected device</em></p>

<h1 id=3D"working-remotely">Working Remotely</h1>
<p>The USB/Local WiFi limitation initially seemed like a big blow the pract=
icality of using Lockdown Services for detections =E2=80=98in the real worl=
d=E2=80=99. Initially I had assumed this limitation was due to the fact the=
 initial device handshake was setup via the <a href=3D"https://developer.ap=
ple.com/bonjour/">Bonjour/Multicast DNS protocol</a>. This protocol by desi=
gn can=E2=80=99t traverse across network subnets, which means the only opti=
on for an iOS device outside of local Wi-Fi range is to connect is to carry=
 around something like <a href=3D"https://www.gl-inet.com/products/gl-x3000=
/">a portable Linux Wi-Fi router</a> that has the ability create a low-leve=
l L2 VPN tunnel to the remote machine, then connect the iOS to the router v=
ia Wi-Fi. Kinda lame.</p>

<p>However, it turns out the initial handshake isn=E2=80=99t strictly neces=
sary every connection. An excellent tool for communicating with <code class=
=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">lockdownd</code> and Lockdown Ser=
vices is <a href=3D"https://github.com/doronz88/pymobiledevice3">pyMobileDe=
vice3</a>, a pure-python implementation of the older  <a href=3D"https://li=
bimobiledevice.org/">libmobiledevice</a> library. This tools provides the a=
bility to communicate with a any remote device that is accessible over TCP,=
 provided it has first been connected =E2=80=98locally=E2=80=99. In my situ=
ation I first connected my iOS device to my remote machine via USB and ran:=
</p>
<div class=3D"language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class=3D"highlight"><pr=
e class=3D"highlight"><code><span class=3D"c"># First, get device identifie=
r from:</span>
pymobiledevice3 usbmux list

<span class=3D"c"># Ensure devices are paired:</span>
pymobiledevice3 lockdown pair

<span class=3D"c"># Turn connections via 'Wi-Fi' on</span>
pymobiledevice3 lockdown wifi-connections on

<span class=3D"c"># Save pair record for future access:</span>
<span class=3D"c"># This contains sensitive data so don't post to Twitter o=
r something</span>
pymobiledevice3 lockdown save-pair-record pair_record.plist
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Once that was done, I was able to connect to my device while it was full=
y remote, as long as it was accessible over TCP, for example using a =E2=80=
=98normal=E2=80=99 VPN like <a href=3D"https://tailscale.com/">Tailscale</a=
> to link the 2 devices together. Using Python on my remote machine, I did =
this by:</p>
<div class=3D"language-python highlighter-rouge"><div class=3D"highlight"><=
pre class=3D"highlight"><code><span class=3D"kn">import</span> <span class=
=3D"nn">plistlib</span>
<span class=3D"kn">from</span> <span class=3D"nn">pymobiledevice3.lockdown<=
/span> <span class=3D"kn">import</span> <span class=3D"n">create_using_tcp<=
/span>

<span class=3D"c1"># Open and parse saved pair record
</span><span class=3D"k">with</span> <span class=3D"nb">open</span><span cl=
ass=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"s">"pair_record.plist"</span><span class=
=3D"p">,</span> <span class=3D"s">"rb"</span><span class=3D"p">)</span> <sp=
an class=3D"k">as</span> <span class=3D"n">f</span><span class=3D"p">:</spa=
n>
  <span class=3D"n">plist</span> <span class=3D"o">=3D</span> <span class=
=3D"n">plistlib</span><span class=3D"p">.</span><span class=3D"n">load</spa=
n><span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">f</span><span class=3D"p">)</=
span>

<span class=3D"n">lockdown</span> <span class=3D"o">=3D</span> <span class=
=3D"n">create_using_tcp</span><span class=3D"p">(</span>
  <span class=3D"c1"># IP Address or hostname of iOS device
</span>  <span class=3D"n">hostname</span><span class=3D"o">=3D</span><span=
 class=3D"s">"10.11.22.33"</span><span class=3D"p">,</span>
  <span class=3D"c1"># Identifier from 'pymobiledevice3 usbmux list'
</span>  <span class=3D"n">identifier</span><span class=3D"o">=3D</span><sp=
an class=3D"s">"11111111-2222222222222222"</span><span class=3D"p">,</span>
  <span class=3D"c1"># plist from disk
</span>  <span class=3D"n">pair_record</span><span class=3D"o">=3D</span><s=
pan class=3D"n">plist</span><span class=3D"p">,</span>
<span class=3D"p">)</span>

<span class=3D"c1"># Can now use lockdown to connect to services, see next =
paragraphs
</span><span class=3D"n">trace_service</span> <span class=3D"o">=3D</span> =
<span class=3D"n">OsTraceService</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span clas=
s=3D"n">lockdown</span><span class=3D"p">)</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>There is a <em>massive</em> caveat with this technique, however - It sti=
ll requires the iOS device to be connected to <em>some type</em> of Wi-Fi n=
etwork. It doesn=E2=80=99t have to be the same Wi-Fi network as the remote =
machine, but unless the device is connected to something over Wi-Fi, the <c=
ode class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">lockdownd</code> daemon =
will refuse any connection. So you could walk around tethered to something =
like a <a href=3D"https://www.unihertz.com/products/jelly-2">small Android =
Phone</a>, and it=E2=80=99d work I guess?</p>

<p>That still isn=E2=80=99t ideal, and I feel there is more research to und=
erstand the exact limitation here. I decided to call this =E2=80=9Cgood eno=
ugh=E2=80=9D for now, and started to look into what you can <em>actually do=
</em> with access the Lockdown services.</p>

<h1 id=3D"unified-logging">Unified Logging</h1>
<p>Like most UNIXes, iOS has a centralised system-wide logging system. Unli=
ke other UNIXs that primarily use syslog, modern iOS uses a system called <=
a href=3D"https://developer.apple.com/documentation/os/logging/">Unified Lo=
gging</a>, which enables applications and programs to produce structured lo=
g entries in that can be performantly written and read in real-time. Manage=
d by the <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">logd</code> d=
aemon on the device, there is no on-device UI to read these logs, mostly be=
cause they are more useful to developers and apple rather than the end-user=
.</p>

<p>Applications can=E2=80=99t access the logs of other applications or syst=
em components, but a paired remote device <em>can</em> read logs from the w=
hole system, by using <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">=
lockdownd</code> to connect to the <a href=3D"https://github.com/doronz88/p=
ymobiledevice3/blob/master/pymobiledevice3/services/os_trace.py#L104">os_tr=
ace_relay</a> Lockdown Service. This is helpfully implemented in pyMobileDe=
vice3, where we can simply run this to start reading and parsing log messag=
es in real-time:</p>
<div class=3D"language-python highlighter-rouge"><div class=3D"highlight"><=
pre class=3D"highlight"><code>
<span class=3D"kn">import</span> <span class=3D"nn">plistlib</span>
<span class=3D"kn">from</span> <span class=3D"nn">pymobiledevice3.lockdown<=
/span> <span class=3D"kn">import</span> <span class=3D"n">create_using_tcp<=
/span>
<span class=3D"kn">from</span> <span class=3D"nn">pymobiledevice3.services.=
os_trace</span> <span class=3D"kn">import</span> <span class=3D"n">OsTraceS=
ervice</span>

<span class=3D"c1"># Connect to os_trace_relay service and start reading en=
tries:
# lockdown =3D create_using_tcp(...)
</span><span class=3D"n">trace_service</span> <span class=3D"o">=3D</span> =
<span class=3D"n">OsTraceService</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span clas=
s=3D"n">lockdown</span><span class=3D"p">)</span>
<span class=3D"k">for</span> <span class=3D"n">entry</span> <span class=3D"=
ow">in</span> <span class=3D"n">trace_service</span><span class=3D"p">.</sp=
an><span class=3D"n">syslog</span><span class=3D"p">():</span>
  <span class=3D"c1"># pyMobileDevice converts this data to a Python object=
.
</span>  <span class=3D"c1"># To write to disk, the below code converts thi=
s into JSON:
</span>  <span class=3D"n">entry_json</span> <span class=3D"o">=3D</span> <=
span class=3D"p">{</span>
        <span class=3D"s">"pid"</span><span class=3D"p">:</span> <span clas=
s=3D"n">entry</span><span class=3D"p">.</span><span class=3D"n">pid</span><=
span class=3D"p">,</span>
        <span class=3D"s">"timestamp"</span><span class=3D"p">:</span> <spa=
