<p>None of this contains port information, but there is an easier way to co=
llect network information from a device=E2=80=A6</p>

<h2 id=3D"networking---using-pcaps">Networking - Using PCAPs</h2>
<p>Starting with iOS 5, apple added a remote virtual interface (RVI) facili=
ty that allows mirroring networks traffic from an iOS device. This is done =
via another Lockdown Service <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-=
rouge">com.apple.pcapd</code>. Helpfully, unlike like a typical external ne=
twork tap, the events received from pcapd contain both the raw traffic and =
information on what Process is responsible for the traffic.</p>

<p>As a demonstration, this code combines pyMobileDevice3 with <a href=3D"h=
ttps://scapy.net/">Scapy</a> to parse unencrypted DNS traffic:</p>
<div class=3D"language-python highlighter-rouge"><div class=3D"highlight"><=
pre class=3D"highlight"><code><span class=3D"kn">from</span> <span class=3D=
"nn">pymobiledevice3.services.pcapd</span> <span class=3D"kn">import</span>=
 <span class=3D"n">PcapdService</span>
<span class=3D"kn">from</span> <span class=3D"nn">scapy.all</span> <span cl=
ass=3D"kn">import</span> <span class=3D"n">sr1</span><span class=3D"p">,</s=
pan><span class=3D"n">IP</span><span class=3D"p">,</span><span class=3D"n">=
ICMP</span><span class=3D"p">,</span> <span class=3D"n">Ether</span><span c=
lass=3D"p">,</span> <span class=3D"n">DNS</span>

<span class=3D"c1"># lockdown =3D create_using_tcp(...)
</span><span class=3D"n">service</span> <span class=3D"o">=3D</span> <span =
class=3D"n">PcapdService</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">=
lockdown</span><span class=3D"p">)</span>
    <span class=3D"k">for</span> <span class=3D"n">packet</span> <span clas=
s=3D"ow">in</span> <span class=3D"n">service</span><span class=3D"p">.</spa=
n><span class=3D"n">watch</span><span class=3D"p">():</span>
        <span class=3D"n">e</span> <span class=3D"o">=3D</span> <span class=
=3D"n">Ether</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">packet</span=
><span class=3D"p">.</span><span class=3D"n">data</span><span class=3D"p">)=
</span>
        <span class=3D"k">if</span> <span class=3D"n">e</span><span class=
=3D"p">.</span><span class=3D"n">haslayer</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><=
span class=3D"n">DNS</span><span class=3D"p">):</span>
            <span class=3D"k">print</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span c=
lass=3D"sa">f</span><span class=3D"s">"epid: </span><span class=3D"si">{</s=
pan><span class=3D"n">packet</span><span class=3D"p">.</span><span class=3D=
"n">epid</span><span class=3D"si">}</span><span class=3D"s"> | pid: </span>=
<span class=3D"si">{</span><span class=3D"n">packet</span><span class=3D"p"=
>.</span><span class=3D"n">pid</span><span class=3D"si">}</span><span class=
=3D"s"> | comm: </span><span class=3D"si">{</span><span class=3D"n">packet<=
/span><span class=3D"p">.</span><span class=3D"n">comm</span><span class=3D=
"si">}</span><span class=3D"s">"</span><span class=3D"p">)</span>
            <span class=3D"k">print</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span c=
lass=3D"n">e</span><span class=3D"p">.</span><span class=3D"n">show</span><=
span class=3D"p">())</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>An example of this code=E2=80=99s output is:</p>
<div class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class=3D"highlight=
"><pre class=3D"highlight"><code>epid: 49370 | pid: 144 | comm: mDNSRespond=
er
###[ Ethernet ]###
  dst       =3D 64:5a:ed:12:5a:4f
  src       =3D 74:ac:b9:37:87:04
  type      =3D IPv4
###[ IP ]###
     version   =3D 4
     ihl       =3D 5
     tos       =3D 0x0
     len       =3D 110
     id        =3D 29395
     flags     =3D DF
     frag      =3D 0
     ttl       =3D 64
     proto     =3D udp
     chksum    =3D 0x4377
     src       =3D 192.168.1.1
     dst       =3D 192.168.1.227
     \options   \
###[ UDP ]###
        sport     =3D domain
        dport     =3D 57369
        len       =3D 90
        chksum    =3D 0x3703
###[ DNS ]###
           id        =3D 39303
           qr        =3D 1
           opcode    =3D QUERY
           aa        =3D 0
           tc        =3D 0
           rd        =3D 1
           ra        =3D 1
           z         =3D 0
           ad        =3D 0
           cd        =3D 0
           rcode     =3D ok
           qdcount   =3D 1
           ancount   =3D 1
           nscount   =3D 0
           arcount   =3D 0
           \qd        \
            |###[ DNS Question Record ]###
            |  qname     =3D b'ec2-13-57-37-224.us-west-1.compute.amazonaws=
.com.'
            |  qtype     =3D A
            |  unicastresponse=3D 0
            |  qclass    =3D IN
           \an        \
            |###[ DNS Resource Record ]###
            |  rrname    =3D b'ec2-13-57-37-224.us-west-1.compute.amazonaws=
.com.'
            |  type      =3D A
            |  cacheflush=3D 0
            |  rclass    =3D IN
            |  ttl       =3D 86400
            |  rdlen     =3D None
            |  rdata     =3D 13.57.37.224
           \ns        \
           \ar        \
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>The <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">pid:144</code> =
and <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">comm:mDNSResponder=
</code> point to the service doing the actual lookup, which in this case is=
 the device=E2=80=99s centralised DNS service But the <code class=3D"langua=
ge-plaintext highlighter-rouge">epid:49370</code> is the Process ID that in=
itiated the DNS lookup, which in this example was <code class=3D"language-p=
laintext highlighter-rouge">curl</code>. By parsing more packets, we would =
see both the initial request, and the actual network connection to <code cl=
ass=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">13.57.37.224</code>.</p>

<p>The caveat to this method is most network data would still be encrypted =
under TLS, including DNS traffic if using DNS-Over-HTTPS/TLS), but the addi=
tion of process information does make this more useful than regular externa=
l network monitoring, as we can can spot situations where an unusual proces=
s is talking to a =E2=80=98normal=E2=80=99 remote server.</p>

<h2 id=3D"file-access">File Access</h2>
<p>The last of the =E2=80=98usual=E2=80=99 events to capture on a system, g=
etting information on interesting files being written to disk also proved d=
ifficult.</p>

<p>One of the more interesting files to observe being written is Crash Logs=
, which might be an indication of a process being exploited and left in an =
unstable state, for example the <a href=3D"https://securitylab.amnesty.org/=
latest/2023/12/pegasus-zero-click-exploit-threatens-journalists-in-india/">=
BLASTPASS attack</a>. Helpfully we get events whenever a new crash report i=
